description: {"blocks":[{"key":"18jqr","text":"Ultrastructural morphological information is routinely obtained from the processing of cells and tissue into plastics for transmission electron microscopy imaging. This technique involves the use of strong chemical fixatives, solvents and resins, which destroy the antigenicity of samples. Freezing samples to a vitreous state using cryo-electron microscopy techniques preserves ultrastructure without the use of harsh chemicals, however, immunolabelling cannot be achieved at temperatures as low as -196 degrees Celsius. Here we describe a protocol for the Tokuyasu technique for cryopreservation and immunolabelling of subcellular structures in cells. Cells are lightly chemically fixed and cryoprotected in sucrose before freezing in liquid nitrogen. Cells are sectioned by cryo-ultramicrotomy and retrieved cryo-sections are thawed. Thawed cryo-sections are then immunolabelled, stained and imaged using a transmission electron microscope. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"as79i","text":"Remove the fixative and wash with phosphate buffered saline (PBS), 3 x 5 mins at room temperature.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"5e7al","text":"Wash with 0.15% glycine in PBS for 10 mins.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"6nvd4","text":"Samples should be embedded in gelatin one at a time from Step 6.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9iv1h","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"dpvmm","text":"Remove 0.15% glycine in PBS and add 1.5ml or 2.5 ml of 1% gelatin in 0.1 M PB (for 6 cm or 10 cm petri dishes, respectively) using a 3ml graduated transfer pipette. {"blocks":[{"key":"5cabt","text":"Trim the front face and edges of the frozen tissue block cutting 50-100 μm deep on all four sides. {"blocks":[{"key":"3prvb","text":"To check the region of interest:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"esmnk","text":"Cut a ribbon of approximately four 60-70 nm ultrathin frozen sections at 0.8 mm/sec and -90 to -120 degrees Celsius using a Leica UC7/FC7 cryo-ultramicrotome and Diatome cryo immuno diamond knife. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"98ac6","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"d7edt","text":"A short ribbon allows the sections to stretch in the pick-up solution once thawed, minimising the occurrence of section wrinkles. {"blocks":[{"key":"5rprq","text":"Cut semi thin frozen sections with a feed of 100-300 nm, at 0.8 mm/sec and at -100 degrees Celsius using a Diatome cryo immuno diamond knife.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"9edlo","text":"Pick up semi thin frozen sections in a 1:1 mixture of 2% methyl cellulose: 2.3 M sucrose in 0.1M PBS (pick-up solution) using a 3 mm stainless steel loop. For details on section retrieval, see Steps 26.1-26.3).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"2ua08","text":"Stain the sections with methylene blue/Azure II or toluidine blue solution for 10-20 seconds on a mini hotplate before rinsing with milliQ water and drying on a mini hotplate.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"550gn","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"3t873","text":"Toluidine blue stains nucleic acids and proteins, enhancing structural detail of semi thin cell sections.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"6lhtm","text":"Observe sections with a wide-field light microscope. If the region of interest has not been obtained, continue trimming and repeat Step 23.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"7i14k","text":"Rinse with PBS, 5 x 2 mins.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Immunogold labelling of ultrathin sections for transmission electron microscopy
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"cugml","text":"Rinse with distilled water, 6 x 1 min.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6o73k","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4nsjh","text":"If the glutaraldehyde is not rinsed out completely, it will react with uranyloxalate (Step 42) to form electron dense precipitates.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

Place the petri dish on ice and add 3 drops of 2% methyl cellulose : 4% uranyl acetate (9 ml : 1 ml) (pH 4.0) to the surface. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"5b41g","text":"Float the grid briefly in the first two drops of methyl cellulose/uranyl acetate, then transfer to the third drop and leave for 10 mins.  ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"2004v","text":"Place a grid in a transmission electron microscope grid holder for high resolution imaging using a transmission electron microscope.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"62ihh","text":" ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"51kt7","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"c3p80","text":"Example: JEOL JEM-1400 Plus TEM at 80 keV equipped with a high sensitivity bottom mount CMOS 'Flash' camera.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"8v59j","text":"Remove the fixative and refresh with normal strength fixative, either 2% paraformaldehyde, 0.2% glutaraldehyde in 0.1 M PB or 4% paraformaldehyde in 0.1 M PB. Seal the petri dish with parafilm and fix cells overnight at 4 degrees Celsius. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"2p819","text":"Optionally, to store samples at 4 degrees Celsius for up to 1 month, remove the fixative and add 1% paraformaldehyde in 0.1 M PB. Place a sheet of parafilm directly over the petri dish, place the lid over the parafilm and seal the lid to the petri dish with more parafilm to prevent desiccation.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"8sb09","text":"Pick up the ultrathin frozen sections in a 1:1 mixture of 2% methyl cellulose : 2.3 M sucrose in PBS (pick-up solution) using a 3 mm stainless steel loop as follows:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"9rjvb","text":"Gently detach adherent cells from the bottom of the petri dish using a cell scraper. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"f3jk8","text":"Transfer the cells to a 1.5 ml microcentrifuge tube using a 3 ml graduated transfer pipette, and pellet the cells immediately using a benchtop microcentrifuge. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"bsopq","text":"Remove the supernatant using a 3 ml fine tip transfer pipette and place the closed microcentrifuge tube containing the cell pellet on a heat block set to 37 degrees Celsius. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"2rd9s","text":"Repeat Steps 6-9 for the remaining samples.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"fm3ao","text":"Add approximately 400 μL to 1000 μL of pre-warmed (37 degrees Celsius) 12% gelatin in 0.1 M PB to the microcentrifuge tube and gently resuspend the cell pellet using a 3 ml graduated transfer pipette. Ensure no air bubbles are present and immediately place the sample on a heat block or in an oven set to 37 degrees Celsius to infuse for 20 to 30 minutes.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5rugr","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"8lhe3","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"a3f8s","text":"Pellet cells using a benchtop microcentrifuge and remove the supernatant leaving a volume of 12% gelatin approximately twice that of the cell pellet (ie 100 μL of 12% gelatin for a 50 μL sized cell pellet).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"bh83v","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"b6equ","text":"Cells will be stacked perpendicular to the g-forces. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"4q591","text":"Solidify the 12% gelatin with cells by cooling at 4 degrees Celsius for 30 minutes. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"sgjl","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7vpnv","text":"12% gelatin provides support to cells so they are easier to handle and facilitates cryosectioning. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"1mb6q","text":"Mount each gelatin-embedded cell block on a clean aluminium bullseye pin. Orient the cell block flat and long side down using forceps, and remove the excess sucrose with a strip of filter paper so the block surface appears shiny and enough sucrose remains at the block base to cement it to the pin. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7in75","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7jea5","text":"If the cell block is too big or too much sucrose is used for mounting, a freezing imbalance between the pin and sample can lead to the formation of cracks at the base of the cell block during freezing. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"f7q1o","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ah402","text":"Blocks larger than 1mm3 should be mounted in the centre of the pin. {"blocks":[{"key":"5uoov","text":"Cut off another piece of the microcentrifuge tube containing the remaining gelatin embedded cell pellet using a razor blade and immediately submerge this in a 2 ml microcentrifuge tube containing ice cold 2.3 M sucrose in PBS. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"7db4t","text":"Wait a few minutes and then carefully remove the gelatin embedded cell pellet from the microcentrifuge tube tip using fine forceps. If the cell pellet does not easily separate from the plastic, return it to the 2.3 M sucrose in PBS and repeat Step 16. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6lb0l","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"1tia6","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"43k42","text":"Place the gelatin embedded cell pellet dome-side up in the drop of ice cold 2.3 M sucrose in PBS and cut the dome twice down the middle into three segments using a scalpel or double edged razor blade. Cut the middle segment into strips and then cut each strip into cubes no larger than 1mm3. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"sup","offset":289,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"3itck","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4pjp4","text":"Strips can be cut into rectangles no more than 1mm wide to identify the orientation of cells.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"mitr","text":"Using forceps, carefully place the gelatin-embedded cell cubes or rectangles into a 2 ml microcentrifuge tube containing ice cold 2.3 M sucrose in PBS, and infuse overnight at 4 degrees Celsius, rotating. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"1a78d","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"d4pke","text":"2.3M sucrose cryoprotects samples so they are vitreous when frozen. Do not infiltrate cell blocks for more than 2 days.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"csfre","text":"Steps 14-19 should ideally be performed in a cold room to prevent condensation of water, which can affect the osmolarity of 2.3 M sucrose in PBS. If a cold room is not available, ensure the sample and sucrose are kept cool using ice.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"e865e","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"f171t","text":"Cut the end off the microcentrifuge tube containing approximately 30 μl of gelatin embedded cells using a razor blade and immediately submerge this in a 2 ml microcentrifuge tube containing ice cold 2.3 M sucrose in PBS.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5fqha","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2nvbl","text":"2.3 M sucrose in PBS shrinks 12% gelatin aiding separation of the embedded cell pellet from the plastic microcentrifuge tube.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"38u6t","text":"Place a Teflon plate on top of a glass petri dish and add a drop of 2.3 M sucrose in PBS to the Teflon plate. If a cold room is not available, cool the Teflon plate by inverting the glass petri dish on ice.   ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"7er5b","text":"Freeze each sample block by gently plunging the pins in liquid nitrogen. For large blocks (\u003e1mm3 ) or blocks with few cells (mostly gelatin), cool the sample pin in the cryo-ultramicrotome chamber at -100 degrees Celsius for 10 mins prior to freezing in liquid nitrogen. Pins should be mounted and frozen one at a time. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"sup","offset":95,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ef29r","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ckrlo","text":"Frozen samples can be stored for years.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Immunogold labelling of ultrathin sections for transmission electron microscopy
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"4qro0","text":"Remove and dry the grid using the looping out method:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Immunogold labelling of ultrathin sections for transmission electron microscopy
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"e4l0k","text":"Clean a remanium wire loop with water and dry.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Immunogold labelling of ultrathin sections for transmission electron microscopy
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"dbruv","text":"Push the loop into the methyl cellulose/uranyl acetate drop and under the grid.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Immunogold labelling of ultrathin sections for transmission electron microscopy
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"amp4n","text":"Lift the grid out from the methyl cellulose/uranyl acetate drop using the loop.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Immunogold labelling of ultrathin sections for transmission electron microscopy
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"43u32","text":"Tilt the loop and grid at a 45-60 degree angle and bring the loop to a piece of filter paper. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Immunogold labelling of ultrathin sections for transmission electron microscopy
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"2mia4","text":"As soon as the loop contacts the filter paper, drag it slowly along the filter paper to remove the excess liquid. A thin film of methyl cellulose/uranyl acetate should remain on the surface of the grid. The slower the drag, the thinner the film.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Immunogold labelling of ultrathin sections for transmission electron microscopy
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"7ecdp","text":"Dry the grid suspended in the loop for 30 minutes at room temperature.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Immunogold labelling of ultrathin sections for transmission electron microscopy
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"7rt4m","text":"Remove the grid from the loop using fine forceps taking care not to tear the methyl cellulose/uranyl acetate film away from the grid. Store grids in a grid storage box.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"1k68u","text":"Dip the stainless steel loop into a microcentrifuge tube containing the pick-up solution to create a thin film of solution over the loop. The droplet must not be too thick (large meniscus) or too thin (no meniscus). ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"2t36e","text":"Bring the stainless steel loop containing the pick-up solution into the cryochamber and towards the ribbon of sections. As soon as the pick-up solution at the edge of the loop starts to freeze white, carefully press the partially frozen droplet onto the ribbon of sections. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"3r2nm","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2ntg8","text":"Take extreme care to avoid damaging the diamond knife edge with the stainless steel loop.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"5sbbs","text":"Retract the stainless steel loop containing the pick-up solution with sections from the cryochamber and wait for the droplet to thaw completely. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"6iqmc","text":"Carefully detach the ribbon of ultrathin frozen sections from the diamond knife edge and drag the ribbon away from the knife edge using an eyelash or Dalmatian hair mounted on a wooden stick (one stick in each hand).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"a4r7c","text":"Transfer the sections to a glass slide by carefully pressing the loop containing the pick-up solution with sections onto the slide.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"5p436","text":"Transfer the sections to 50-150 mesh copper or palladium-coated copper grids with carbon-coated formvar film by carefully pressing the loop containing the pick-up solution with sections onto the grid.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9ohsj","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4jvp0","text":"During formvar film preparation, coated grids are secured to a sheet of parafilm on a glass slide.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"1g1sk","text":"Sample grids immersed in pick-up solution can be stored for several years in a sealed petri dish at 4 degrees Celsius until further use.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
